[In order to speculate on the causal agent (or agents) of this outbreak, it is important to know what symptoms were present in those affected -- that is, nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea or any other symptoms (especially neurological) as well as the incubation period from ingestion of the alleged vehicle and the development of symptoms. In addition to the possibility that "garden variety" staphylococcal enterotoxin (short incubation period, primarily vomiting without fever) or salmonellosis or _Vibrio parahaemolyticus_ infection (longer incubation period, primarily diarrhea with fever) for examples which might be associated with foods other than the mussels; shellfish can be linked to several other relatively short incubation illnesses including norovirus and 2 of the so-called shellfish poisoning diseases, diarrheal (or diarrhetic) shellfish poisoning and neurotoxic shellfish poisoning. ProMED-mail would appreciate more information about this outbreak.

Diarrhetic shellfish poisoning (DSP) [1] is an acute gastrointestinal illness caused by consumption of bivalve molluscs that have accumulated okadaic acid (OA) or related dinophysistoxins through the mollusks' use of filter feeding. Symptoms include nausea, abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhea, headache, chills, and fever with an incubation period of 30 minutes to 4 hours after consumption of contaminated food, and symptoms last up to 72 hours; treatment is supportive. The symptoms are quite similar to norovirus disease.

Neurotoxic shellfish poisoning (NSP) [2] is caused by consumption of molluscan shellfish contaminated with brevetoxins. Brevetoxins are neurotoxins which activate voltage-sensitive sodium channels causing sodium influx and nerve membrane depolarization. No fatalities have been reported, but hospitalizations occur. NSP involves a cluster of gastrointestinal and neurological symptoms: nausea and vomiting, paresthesias of the mouth, lips and tongue as well as distal paresthesias, ataxia, slurred speech and dizziness. Neurological symptoms can progress to partial paralysis; respiratory distress has been recorded.

Muar (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muar_(town)) is a historical town and the capital of Muar District, Johor, Malaysia. It is one of the most popular tourist attractions in Malaysia and explored for its food, coffee and historical buildings from the pre-war period. An alternative name to it is Bandar Maharani. A map of its location in southern Malaysia can be found at this URL.

References
----------
1. Lloyd JK, Duchin JS, Borchert J, Quintana HF and Robertson A. Diarrhetic shellfish poisoning, Washington, USA, 2011. Emerg Infect Dis. 2013;19(8):1314-6, available at https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3739508/.
2. Watkins SM, Reich A, Fleming LE, Hammond R. Neurotoxic shellfish poisoning. Mar Drugs. 2008;6(3):431-55, available at https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2579735/.
